{"repo": "pyscf/pyscf", "pull_number": 3065, "instance_id": "pyscf__pyscf-3065", "issue_numbers": [624], "base_commit": "8373e6558c79d2fb93c6dd64106d01903330c072", "patch": "diff --git a/examples/geomopt/01-ase.py b/examples/geomopt/01-ase.py\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..82e92a8a08\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/examples/geomopt/01-ase.py\n@@ -0,0 +1,16 @@\n+#!/usr/bin/env python\n+\n+'''\n+Geometry optimization with ASE\n+\n+ASE uses the BFGS optimizer by default. This general-purpose algorithm is often\n+not as efficient as dedicated geometry optimizers such as Berny or geomeTRIC.\n+'''\n+\n+import pyscf\n+\n+mol = pyscf.M(atom='N 0 0 0; N 0 0 1.2', basis='ccpvdz')\n+mf_opt = mol.RHF().Gradients().optimizer(solver='ase')\n+\n+mol_eq = mf_opt.kernel()\n+print(mol_eq.tostring())\ndiff --git a/examples/pbc/09-ase_geometry_optimization.py b/examples/pbc/09-ase_geometry_optimization.py\nindex ad5e5a081f..d5639f2ead 100644\n--- a/examples/pbc/09-ase_geometry_optimization.py\n+++ b/examples/pbc/09-ase_geometry_optimization.py\n@@ -26,7 +26,7 @@\n # However, some methods may not support gradients or stress tensors. Geometry\n # optimization or lattice optimization that rely on these functionalities will\n # be halted.\n-atoms.set_calculator(PySCF(method=mf))\n+atoms.calc = PySCF(method=mf)\n \n # optimize atom positions\n opt = BFGS(atoms, logfile='atom_pos.log')\ndiff --git a/examples/pbc/09-talk_to_ase.py b/examples/pbc/09-talk_to_ase.py\nindex 87c0eb1d9b..b2f976cc2a 100644\n--- a/examples/pbc/09-talk_to_ase.py\n+++ b/examples/pbc/09-talk_to_ase.py\n@@ -34,7 +34,7 @@\n mf = cell.KRKS(xc='lda,vwn', kpts=cell.make_kpts([2,2,2]))\n \n # Once this is setup, ASE is used for everything from this point on\n-ase_atom.set_calculator(pyscf_ase.PySCF(method=mf))\n+ase_atom.calc = pyscf_ase.PySCF(method=mf)\n \n print(\"ASE energy\", ase_atom.get_potential_energy())\n print(\"ASE energy (should avoid re-evaluation)\", ase_atom.get_potential_energy())\ndiff --git a/examples/tools/08-ase_calculator.py b/examples/tools/08-ase_calculator.py\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..9ff6822343\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/examples/tools/08-ase_calculator.py\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+#!/usr/bin/env python\n+\n+'''\n+Using PySCF as an ASE Calculator\n+\n+Any PySCF mean-field or post-mean-field method (e.g., DFT, HF, CCSD) can be\n+wrapped as an ASE-compatible calculator using the pyscf_ase interface.\n+\n+More examples can be found in examples/pbc/09-ase_geometry_optimization.py and\n+examples/pbc/09-talk_to_ase.py\n+'''\n+\n+import pyscf\n+from pyscf.pbc.tools.pyscf_ase import PySCF, ase_atoms_to_pyscf\n+from ase import Atoms\n+\n+# Define molecules using ase.Atoms class, the ase_atoms_to_pyscf function can\n+# convert the geometry to pyscf input format\n+atoms = Atoms('N2', [(0, 0, 0), (0, 0, 1.2)])\n+mol = pyscf.M(atom=ase_atoms_to_pyscf(atoms), basis='ccpvdz')\n+\n+# Example 1: Use a DFT method as an ASE calculator\n+mf = mol.RKS(xc='pbe0')\n+atoms.calc = PySCF(method=mf)\n+\n+# Example 2: Use a post-HF method (CCSD) as an ASE calculator\n+atoms.calc = PySCF(method=mol.RHF().CCSD())\ndiff --git a/pyscf/pbc/tools/pyscf_ase.py b/pyscf/pbc/tools/pyscf_ase.py\nindex 05fa7d0779..6e779aaa53 100644\n--- a/pyscf/pbc/tools/pyscf_ase.py\n+++ b/pyscf/pbc/tools/pyscf_ase.py\n@@ -1,5 +1,5 @@\n #!/usr/bin/env python\n-# Copyright 2014-2020 The PySCF Developers. All Rights Reserved.\n+# Copyright 2014-2025 The PySCF Developers. All Rights Reserved.\n #\n # Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n # you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n@@ -21,8 +21,15 @@\n ASE package interface\n '''\n \n+try:\n+    from ase.calculators.calculator import Calculator, all_properties\n+except ImportError:\n+    print(\"\"\"ASE is not found. Please install ASE via\n+pip3 install ase\n+          \"\"\")\n+    raise RuntimeError(\"ASE is not found\")\n+\n import numpy as np\n-from ase.calculators.calculator import Calculator, all_properties\n from ase.units import Debye\n from pyscf import lib\n from pyscf.data.nist import BOHR, HARTREE2EV\n@@ -65,7 +72,7 @@ def cell_from_ase(ase_atoms):\n \n class PySCF(Calculator):\n     implemented_properties = ['energy', 'forces', 'stress',\n-                              'dipole', 'magmom']\n+                              'dipole', 'magmom', 'polarizability']\n \n     default_parameters = {}\n \n@@ -159,9 +166,20 @@ def calculate(self, atoms=None, properties=['energy'],\n             # in Gaussian cgs unit\n             self.results['dipole'] = base_method.dip_moment() * Debye\n \n+        if 'polarizability' in properties:\n+            assert hasattr(base_method, 'istype') and base_method.istype('SCF'), \\\n+                    'Polarizability can only be computed with mean-field methods'\n+            if self.pbc:\n+                from pyscf.pbc.prop.polarizability.rhf import Polarizability\n+                p = Polarizability(base_method).polarizability()\n+            else:\n+                from pyscf.prop.polarizability import rhf, uhf\n+                if base_method.istype('UHF'):\n+                    p = uhf.Polarizability(base_method).polarizability()\n+                else:\n+                    p = rhf.Polarizability(base_method).polarizability()\n+            self.results['polarizability'] = p * (BOHR**3)\n+\n         if 'magmom' in properties:\n             magmom = self.mol.spin\n             self.results['magmom'] = magmom\n-\n-def make_kpts(cell, nks):\n-    raise DeprecationWarning('Use cell.make_kpts(nks) instead.')\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Is it possible to create a PySCF-based ASE calculator with only mf as input?\nHi,\r\n\r\nI really enjoy working with PySCF, and tried to construct an Atomic Simulation Environment calculator that only depends on a PySCF-style mf object as parameter.   \r\nI've called the calculator PYMOL, since it is designed for molecules, and it can be found in the attached python script - pymol.py.  \r\n\r\n[pymol.zip](https://github.com/pyscf/pyscf/files/4718050/pymol.zip)\r\n\r\n Everything seems fine, until I start a geometry optimization using ASE and ask for the construction of a trajectory file.  Using the example presented at the bottom of the pymol.py, I receive the following error:  \r\n**TypeError: Object of type UKS is not JSON serializable**  \r\nAs mentioned, if I do not print a trajectory file, everything seems fine.   \r\nIs an ASE calculator based only on a PySCF mf object doomed from the start, or have I missed something?  \r\n\r\nI really appreciate the time and effort that goes into answering this question, and again, I am very\r\nthankful for your work on this code.  \r\n\r\nBest regards  \r\n\r\nJakob Kraus\r\n\r\n\n", "hints_text": "It's not doomed, but a bit more effort is needed to support ASE out of the\nbox. A little bit was done early on in the PBC module, but if you are\ninterested in doing a little bit of development work it would be quite easy\nto add such support. We would be happy to help you with that, or we can tag\nit as an enhancement.\n\nOn Tue, Jun 2, 2020 at 8:13 AM Jakob Kraus <notifications@github.com> wrote:\n\n> Hi,\n>\n> I really enjoy working with PySCF, and tried to construct an Atomic\n> Simulation Environment calculator that only depends on a PySCF-style mf\n> object as parameter.\n> I've called the calculator PYMOL, since it is designed for molecules, and\n> it can be found in the attached python script - pymol.py. Everything seems\n> fine, until I start a geometry optimization using ASE and ask for the\n> construction of a trajectory file. Using the example presented at the\n> bottom of the pymol.py, I receive the following error:\n> *TypeError: Object of type UKS is not JSON serializable*\n> As mentioned, if I do not print a trajectory file, everything seems fine.\n> Is an ASE calculator based only on a PySCF mf object doomed from the\n> start, or have I missed something?\n>\n> I really appreciate the time and effort that goes into answering this\n> question, and again, I am very\n> thankful for your work on this code.\n>\n> Best regards\n>\n> Jakob Kraus\n>\n> \u2014\n> You are receiving this because you are subscribed to this thread.\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\n> <https://github.com/pyscf/pyscf/issues/624>, or unsubscribe\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/AAN5NRBPENHLOUSHONX2JA3RUUJKTANCNFSM4NQ2H6GA>\n> .\n>\n\nThanks for the very quick response.\r\nI'm interested in helping as much as I can - development work included - , but pymol.py is as far as I got, and I do not know which steps are needed now in order to make the calculator fully work as intended.\nFollowing is a simple workaround.\r\n```\r\nfrom pyscf import dft\r\nclass UKS(dft.uks.UKS):\r\n    def todict(self):\r\n        import jsonpickle\r\n        return jsonpickle.encode(self, unpicklable=False)\r\n\r\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\r\n\r\n    from pyscf import gto, dft\r\n    from ase.optimize import FIRE\r\n    from ase.io import read\r\n\r\n    basis = 'STO-3G'\r\n    spin = 0\r\n    charge = 0\r\n\r\n    atoms = read('formic_acid.xyz')\r\n\r\n    mol = gto.M(\r\n        atom=atoms_from_ase(atoms),\r\n        basis=basis,\r\n        spin=spin,\r\n        charge=charge)\r\n\r\n    mf = UKS(mol)\r\n    mf.xc = 'lda,pw'\r\n    mf.max_cycle = 300\r\n    mf.conv_tol = 1e-6\r\n    mf.verbose = 4\r\n\r\n    calc = PYMOL(mf=mf)\r\n    atoms.set_calculator(calc)\r\n    # perform a geometry optimization\r\n    opt = FIRE(atoms, logfile='atoms.log', trajectory='atoms.traj')\r\n    opt.run(fmax=0.0075, steps=3)\r\n```\r\nBut in order to read the trajectory file, you probably also need to implement a JSON decode method for UKS.\r\n\nThank you very much for the nice workaround! I was able to read the trajectory file using the trajectory tools implemented in ASE. I am currently using another variant of your workaround, where the todict() method is added to self.mf in the initialize function via self.mf.todict = lambda: todict(self.mf) and todict(x) being defined just like in your workaround.\r\n\nHi everyone,  \r\nthanks to your input I managed to craft a new PySCF calculator\r\nwhich seems to work well enough for DFT, HF, CISD, CCSD, CCSD(T) (with CCSD gradients), and MP2.\r\nSince forces and dipole moments are evaluated in addition to the energy, this calculator should work with the geometry optimization, vibrational analysis, and infrared functionalities implemented in ASE.\r\nIf you have noticed bugs or have ideas for improvement, feel free to comment!\r\n\r\n```\r\nimport numpy\r\nfrom ase.calculators.calculator import Calculator, all_changes\r\nfrom ase.units import Ha, Bohr, Debye\r\nfrom pyscf.prop.polarizability.uhf import polarizability, Polarizability\r\nfrom pyscf.pbc.tools.pyscf_ase import atoms_from_ase\r\nimport jsonpickle\r\n\r\nclass parameters():\r\n    # holds the calculation mode and user-chosen attributes of post-HF objects\r\n    def __init__(self):\r\n        self.mode = 'hf'\r\n    def show(self):\r\n        print('------------------------')\r\n        print('calculation-specific parameters set by the user')\r\n        print('------------------------')\r\n        for v in vars(self):\r\n            print('{}:  {}'.format(v,vars(self)[v]))\r\n        print('\\n\\n')\r\n                                                         \r\n\r\n\r\ndef todict(x):\r\n    return jsonpickle.encode(x, unpicklable=False)\r\n\r\n\r\ndef init_geo(mf, atoms):\r\n    # convert ASE structural information to PySCF information\r\n    if atoms.pbc.any():\r\n        cell = mf.cell.copy()\r\n        cell.atom = atoms_from_ase(atoms)\r\n        cell.a = atoms.cell.copy()\r\n        cell.build()\r\n        mf.reset(cell=cell.copy())\r\n    else:\r\n        mol = mf.mol.copy()\r\n        mol.atom = atoms_from_ase(atoms)\r\n        mol.build()\r\n        mf.reset(mol=mol.copy())\r\n\r\nclass PYSCF(Calculator):\r\n    # PySCF ASE calculator\r\n    # by Jakob Kraus\r\n    # units:  ase         -> units [eV,Angstroem,eV/Angstroem,e*A,A**3]\r\n    #         pyscf       -> units [Ha,Bohr,Ha/Bohr,Debye,Bohr**3]\r\n\r\n    implemented_properties = ['energy','forces','dipole','polarizability']\r\n    \r\n    \r\n    def __init__(self, restart=None, ignore_bad_restart_file=False,\r\n                 label='PySCF', atoms=None, directory='.', **kwargs):\r\n        # constructor\r\n        Calculator.__init__(self, restart, ignore_bad_restart_file,\r\n                            label, atoms, directory, **kwargs)\r\n        self.initialize(**kwargs)\r\n\r\n\r\n    def initialize(self, mf=None, p=None):\r\n        # attach the mf object to the calculator\r\n        # add the todict functionality to enable ASE trajectories:\r\n        # https://github.com/pyscf/pyscf/issues/624\r\n        self.mf = mf\r\n        self.p = p\r\n        self.mf.todict = lambda: todict(self.mf)\r\n        self.p.todict = lambda: todict(self.p)\r\n\r\n    def set(self, **kwargs):\r\n        # allow for a calculator reset\r\n        changed_parameters = Calculator.set(self, **kwargs)\r\n        if changed_parameters:\r\n            self.reset()\r\n    \r\n    def get_polarizability(self,atoms=None):\r\n        return self.get_property('polarizability',atoms)\r\n    \r\n    def calculate(self,atoms=None,properties=['energy'],system_changes=all_changes):\r\n        \r\n        Calculator.calculate(self,atoms=atoms,properties=properties,system_changes=system_changes)\r\n        \r\n        # update your mf object with new structural information\r\n        init_geo(self.mf, atoms)\r\n\r\n        # further update your mf object for post-HF methods\r\n        if hasattr(self.mf,'_scf'):\r\n            self.mf._scf.kernel()\r\n            self.mf.__init__(self.mf._scf)\r\n            for v in vars(self.p):\r\n                if v != 'mode':\r\n                    setattr(self.mf,v,vars(self.p)[v])\r\n        self.mf.kernel()\r\n        e = self.mf.e_tot\r\n        \r\n        if self.p.mode.lower() == 'ccsd(t)':\r\n            e += self.mf.ccsd_t()\r\n        \r\n        self.results['energy'] = e * Ha\r\n        \r\n        if 'forces' in properties:\r\n            gf = self.mf.nuc_grad_method()\r\n            gf.verbose = self.mf.verbose\r\n            if self.p.mode.lower() == 'dft':\r\n                gf.grid_response = True\r\n            forces = -1. * gf.kernel() * (Ha / Bohr)\r\n            totalforces = []\r\n            totalforces.extend(forces)\r\n            totalforces = numpy.array(totalforces)\r\n            self.results['forces'] = totalforces\r\n        \r\n        if hasattr(self.mf,'_scf'):\r\n            self.results['dipole'] = self.mf._scf.dip_moment(verbose=self.mf._scf.verbose) * Debye\r\n            self.results['polarizability'] = Polarizability(self.mf._scf).polarizability() * (Bohr**3)\r\n        else:\r\n            self.results['dipole'] = self.mf.dip_moment(verbose=self.mf.verbose) * Debye\r\n            self.results['polarizability'] = Polarizability(self.mf).polarizability() * (Bohr**3)\r\n\r\nif __name__ == '__main__':\r\n\r\n    import pyscf\r\n    from ase import Atoms\r\n    from ase.optimize import LBFGS\r\n    \r\n    atoms = Atoms('H2', [(0, 0, 0), (0, 0, 1)])\r\n    mol = pyscf.M(atom=atoms_from_ase(atoms),basis='cc-pVDZ',spin=0,charge=0)\r\n\r\n    mf = mol.UHF()\r\n    mf.verbose = 3\r\n    mf.kernel() \r\n    \r\n    index = 4\r\n\r\n    mf = [mf,mf.MP2(),mf.CISD(),mf.CCSD(),mf.CCSD()][index]\r\n    \r\n    p = parameters()\r\n    p.mode = ['hf','mp2','cisd','ccsd','ccsd(t)'][index]\r\n    p.verbose = 5\r\n    p.show()\r\n\r\n    mf.verbose = p.verbose\r\n    atoms.calc = PYSCF(mf=mf,p=p)\r\n\r\n    \r\n    fmax = 1e-3 * (Ha / Bohr)\r\n    \r\n    dyn = LBFGS(atoms,logfile='opt.log',trajectory='opt.traj')\r\n    dyn.run(fmax=fmax)\r\n```\n\n", "all_hints_text": "It's not doomed, but a bit more effort is needed to support ASE out of the\nbox. A little bit was done early on in the PBC module, but if you are\ninterested in doing a little bit of development work it would be quite easy\nto add such support. We would be happy to help you with that, or we can tag\nit as an enhancement.\n\nOn Tue, Jun 2, 2020 at 8:13 AM Jakob Kraus <notifications@github.com> wrote:\n\n> Hi,\n>\n> I really enjoy working with PySCF, and tried to construct an Atomic\n> Simulation Environment calculator that only depends on a PySCF-style mf\n> object as parameter.\n> I've called the calculator PYMOL, since it is designed for molecules, and\n> it can be found in the attached python script - pymol.py. Everything seems\n> fine, until I start a geometry optimization using ASE and ask for the\n> construction of a trajectory file. Using the example presented at the\n> bottom of the pymol.py, I receive the following error:\n> *TypeError: Object of type UKS is not JSON serializable*\n> As mentioned, if I do not print a trajectory file, everything seems fine.\n> Is an ASE calculator based only on a PySCF mf object doomed from the\n> start, or have I missed something?\n>\n> I really appreciate the time and effort that goes into answering this\n> question, and again, I am very\n> thankful for your work on this code.\n>\n> Best regards\n>\n> Jakob Kraus\n>\n> \u2014\n> You are receiving this because you are subscribed to this thread.\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\n> <https://github.com/pyscf/pyscf/issues/624>, or unsubscribe\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/AAN5NRBPENHLOUSHONX2JA3RUUJKTANCNFSM4NQ2H6GA>\n> .\n>\n\nThanks for the very quick response.\r\nI'm interested in helping as much as I can - development work included - , but pymol.py is as far as I got, and I do not know which steps are needed now in order to make the calculator fully work as intended.\nFollowing is a simple workaround.\r\n```\r\nfrom pyscf import dft\r\nclass UKS(dft.uks.UKS):\r\n    def todict(self):\r\n        import jsonpickle\r\n        return jsonpickle.encode(self, unpicklable=False)\r\n\r\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\r\n\r\n    from pyscf import gto, dft\r\n    from ase.optimize import FIRE\r\n    from ase.io import read\r\n\r\n    basis = 'STO-3G'\r\n    spin = 0\r\n    charge = 0\r\n\r\n    atoms = read('formic_acid.xyz')\r\n\r\n    mol = gto.M(\r\n        atom=atoms_from_ase(atoms),\r\n        basis=basis,\r\n        spin=spin,\r\n        charge=charge)\r\n\r\n    mf = UKS(mol)\r\n    mf.xc = 'lda,pw'\r\n    mf.max_cycle = 300\r\n    mf.conv_tol = 1e-6\r\n    mf.verbose = 4\r\n\r\n    calc = PYMOL(mf=mf)\r\n    atoms.set_calculator(calc)\r\n    # perform a geometry optimization\r\n    opt = FIRE(atoms, logfile='atoms.log', trajectory='atoms.traj')\r\n    opt.run(fmax=0.0075, steps=3)\r\n```\r\nBut in order to read the trajectory file, you probably also need to implement a JSON decode method for UKS.\r\n\nThank you very much for the nice workaround! I was able to read the trajectory file using the trajectory tools implemented in ASE. I am currently using another variant of your workaround, where the todict() method is added to self.mf in the initialize function via self.mf.todict = lambda: todict(self.mf) and todict(x) being defined just like in your workaround.\r\n\nHi everyone,  \r\nthanks to your input I managed to craft a new PySCF calculator\r\nwhich seems to work well enough for DFT, HF, CISD, CCSD, CCSD(T) (with CCSD gradients), and MP2.\r\nSince forces and dipole moments are evaluated in addition to the energy, this calculator should work with the geometry optimization, vibrational analysis, and infrared functionalities implemented in ASE.\r\nIf you have noticed bugs or have ideas for improvement, feel free to comment!\r\n\r\n```\r\nimport numpy\r\nfrom ase.calculators.calculator import Calculator, all_changes\r\nfrom ase.units import Ha, Bohr, Debye\r\nfrom pyscf.prop.polarizability.uhf import polarizability, Polarizability\r\nfrom pyscf.pbc.tools.pyscf_ase import atoms_from_ase\r\nimport jsonpickle\r\n\r\nclass parameters():\r\n    # holds the calculation mode and user-chosen attributes of post-HF objects\r\n    def __init__(self):\r\n        self.mode = 'hf'\r\n    def show(self):\r\n        print('------------------------')\r\n        print('calculation-specific parameters set by the user')\r\n        print('------------------------')\r\n        for v in vars(self):\r\n            print('{}:  {}'.format(v,vars(self)[v]))\r\n        print('\\n\\n')\r\n                                                         \r\n\r\n\r\ndef todict(x):\r\n    return jsonpickle.encode(x, unpicklable=False)\r\n\r\n\r\ndef init_geo(mf, atoms):\r\n    # convert ASE structural information to PySCF information\r\n    if atoms.pbc.any():\r\n        cell = mf.cell.copy()\r\n        cell.atom = atoms_from_ase(atoms)\r\n        cell.a = atoms.cell.copy()\r\n        cell.build()\r\n        mf.reset(cell=cell.copy())\r\n    else:\r\n        mol = mf.mol.copy()\r\n        mol.atom = atoms_from_ase(atoms)\r\n        mol.build()\r\n        mf.reset(mol=mol.copy())\r\n\r\nclass PYSCF(Calculator):\r\n    # PySCF ASE calculator\r\n    # by Jakob Kraus\r\n    # units:  ase         -> units [eV,Angstroem,eV/Angstroem,e*A,A**3]\r\n    #         pyscf       -> units [Ha,Bohr,Ha/Bohr,Debye,Bohr**3]\r\n\r\n    implemented_properties = ['energy','forces','dipole','polarizability']\r\n    \r\n    \r\n    def __init__(self, restart=None, ignore_bad_restart_file=False,\r\n                 label='PySCF', atoms=None, directory='.', **kwargs):\r\n        # constructor\r\n        Calculator.__init__(self, restart, ignore_bad_restart_file,\r\n                            label, atoms, directory, **kwargs)\r\n        self.initialize(**kwargs)\r\n\r\n\r\n    def initialize(self, mf=None, p=None):\r\n        # attach the mf object to the calculator\r\n        # add the todict functionality to enable ASE trajectories:\r\n        # https://github.com/pyscf/pyscf/issues/624\r\n        self.mf = mf\r\n        self.p = p\r\n        self.mf.todict = lambda: todict(self.mf)\r\n        self.p.todict = lambda: todict(self.p)\r\n\r\n    def set(self, **kwargs):\r\n        # allow for a calculator reset\r\n        changed_parameters = Calculator.set(self, **kwargs)\r\n        if changed_parameters:\r\n            self.reset()\r\n    \r\n    def get_polarizability(self,atoms=None):\r\n        return self.get_property('polarizability',atoms)\r\n    \r\n    def calculate(self,atoms=None,properties=['energy'],system_changes=all_changes):\r\n        \r\n        Calculator.calculate(self,atoms=atoms,properties=properties,system_changes=system_changes)\r\n        \r\n        # update your mf object with new structural information\r\n        init_geo(self.mf, atoms)\r\n\r\n        # further update your mf object for post-HF methods\r\n        if hasattr(self.mf,'_scf'):\r\n            self.mf._scf.kernel()\r\n            self.mf.__init__(self.mf._scf)\r\n            for v in vars(self.p):\r\n                if v != 'mode':\r\n                    setattr(self.mf,v,vars(self.p)[v])\r\n        self.mf.kernel()\r\n        e = self.mf.e_tot\r\n        \r\n        if self.p.mode.lower() == 'ccsd(t)':\r\n            e += self.mf.ccsd_t()\r\n        \r\n        self.results['energy'] = e * Ha\r\n        \r\n        if 'forces' in properties:\r\n            gf = self.mf.nuc_grad_method()\r\n            gf.verbose = self.mf.verbose\r\n            if self.p.mode.lower() == 'dft':\r\n                gf.grid_response = True\r\n            forces = -1. * gf.kernel() * (Ha / Bohr)\r\n            totalforces = []\r\n            totalforces.extend(forces)\r\n            totalforces = numpy.array(totalforces)\r\n            self.results['forces'] = totalforces\r\n        \r\n        if hasattr(self.mf,'_scf'):\r\n            self.results['dipole'] = self.mf._scf.dip_moment(verbose=self.mf._scf.verbose) * Debye\r\n            self.results['polarizability'] = Polarizability(self.mf._scf).polarizability() * (Bohr**3)\r\n        else:\r\n            self.results['dipole'] = self.mf.dip_moment(verbose=self.mf.verbose) * Debye\r\n            self.results['polarizability'] = Polarizability(self.mf).polarizability() * (Bohr**3)\r\n\r\nif __name__ == '__main__':\r\n\r\n    import pyscf\r\n    from ase import Atoms\r\n    from ase.optimize import LBFGS\r\n    \r\n    atoms = Atoms('H2', [(0, 0, 0), (0, 0, 1)])\r\n    mol = pyscf.M(atom=atoms_from_ase(atoms),basis='cc-pVDZ',spin=0,charge=0)\r\n\r\n    mf = mol.UHF()\r\n    mf.verbose = 3\r\n    mf.kernel() \r\n    \r\n    index = 4\r\n\r\n    mf = [mf,mf.MP2(),mf.CISD(),mf.CCSD(),mf.CCSD()][index]\r\n    \r\n    p = parameters()\r\n    p.mode = ['hf','mp2','cisd','ccsd','ccsd(t)'][index]\r\n    p.verbose = 5\r\n    p.show()\r\n\r\n    mf.verbose = p.verbose\r\n    atoms.calc = PYSCF(mf=mf,p=p)\r\n\r\n    \r\n    fmax = 1e-3 * (Ha / Bohr)\r\n    \r\n    dyn = LBFGS(atoms,logfile='opt.log',trajectory='opt.traj')\r\n    dyn.run(fmax=fmax)\r\n```\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/pyscf/pyscf/commit/ede68dc57264829e7cb10e718785f18a876c41f3", "https://github.com/pyscf/pyscf/commit/fb406f7a5452befc3c4aace927da3999dad65ad3", "https://github.com/pyscf/pyscf/commit/16951fdac327958b6139033c168be85130c9046b"], "created_at": "2025-12-07T01:10:41Z"}
{"repo": "pyscf/pyscf", "pull_number": 3196, "instance_id": "pyscf__pyscf-3196", "issue_numbers": [2401, 2967], "base_commit": "e620426d1bc1385bf09437e3c14cdc7019781880", "patch": "diff --git a/pyscf/hessian/thermo.py b/pyscf/hessian/thermo.py\nindex f7d4d0d0c8..15452197e1 100644\n--- a/pyscf/hessian/thermo.py\n+++ b/pyscf/hessian/thermo.py\n@@ -119,6 +119,7 @@ def rotation_const(mass, atom_coords, unit='GHz'):\n     im = numpy.einsum('z,zr,zs->rs', mass, r, r)\n     im = numpy.eye(3) * im.trace() - im\n     e = numpy.sort(numpy.linalg.eigvalsh(im))\n+    e[abs(e) < 1e-9] = 0.0\n \n     unit_im = nist.ATOMIC_MASS * (nist.BOHR_SI)**2\n     unit_hz = nist.HBAR / (4 * numpy.pi * unit_im)\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/pyscf/hessian/test/test_thermo.py b/pyscf/hessian/test/test_thermo.py\nindex 869f3b5877..2e9913646d 100644\n--- a/pyscf/hessian/test/test_thermo.py\n+++ b/pyscf/hessian/test/test_thermo.py\n@@ -63,9 +63,20 @@ def test_rotation_const(self):\n         self.assertTrue(c[1] == numpy.inf)\n         self.assertTrue(c[2] == numpy.inf)\n \n+    def test_rotor_type(self):\n+        mol = gto.M(atom='O 6.49389522e-15 -2.57224363e-14 -3.70463374e-03; O -6.49389522e-15 2.57224363e-14 1.21370463e+00')\n+        mass = mol.atom_mass_list(isotope_avg=True)\n+        atom_coords = mol.atom_coords()\n+        mass_center = numpy.einsum('z,zx->x', mass, atom_coords) / mass.sum()\n+        atom_coords = atom_coords - mass_center\n+        rot_const = thermo.rotation_const(mass, atom_coords)\n+        self.assertEqual(rot_const[0], numpy.inf)\n+        rotor_type = thermo._get_rotor_type(rot_const)\n+        self.assertEqual(rotor_type, 'LINEAR')\n+\n     def test_thermo(self):\n         mol = gto.M(atom='O 0 0 0; H 0 .757 .587; H 0 -.757 .587')\n-        mf = mol.HF.run(conv_tol=1e-11)\n+        mf = mol.HF().run(conv_tol=1e-11)\n         hess = mf.Hessian().kernel()\n         results = thermo.harmonic_analysis(mol, hess)\n         self.assertAlmostEqual(lib.fp(abs(results['norm_mode'])), 0.1144453655, 6)\n", "problem_statement": "A problem in determining the rotor type with hessian.thermo\nHi there,\r\n\r\nI encountered several problems when using functions in `pyscf.hessian.thermo` for the HCl molecule. I found that it was because `_get_rotor_type()` decided HCl is `REGULAR`, not `LINEAR`.  \r\n\r\nIn the `_get_rotor_type()` function, the condition for the molecule to be `LINEAR` is `rot_const[0] > 1e8 and (rot_const[1] - rot_const[2] < 1e-3)`. However, the `rot_const[0]` for my HCl molecule was -4e18.\r\n\r\nTherefore, my question is, should there be an absolute value function on `rot_const[0]` in the above condition? \r\n\r\nThanks,\r\nChong\n[BUG REPORT] Pyscf sometimes recognizes a diatomic molecule as a \"regular\" (non-linear) molecule\n**Describe the bug**\nPyscf sometimes recognizes a diatomic molecule as a \"regular\" (non-linear) molecule. \n\n**To Reproduce**\n```python\nimport numpy as np\nfrom pyscf.hessian.thermo import harmonic_analysis\nfrom pyscf import gto\nfrom pyscf.hessian.thermo import rotation_const, _get_rotor_type\n\nxyz_coordinates = [[ 6.49389522e-15,-2.57224363e-14,-3.70463374e-03],[-6.49389522e-15,2.57224363e-14,1.21370463e+00]]\npyscf_mol = gto.Mole()\npyscf_mol.atom = [['O', tuple(a)] for a in xyz_coordinates]\npyscf_mol.verbose = 0\npyscf_mol.build()\n\n\nmass = pyscf_mol.atom_mass_list(isotope_avg=True)\natom_coords = pyscf_mol.atom_coords()\nmass_center = np.einsum('z,zx->x', mass, atom_coords) / mass.sum()\natom_coords = atom_coords - mass_center\nrot_const = rotation_const(mass, atom_coords)\nprint(rot_const)\nrotor_type = _get_rotor_type(rot_const)\nprint(rotor_type)\n```\n\n**Expected behavior**\nThe above codes calculate the rotation constants and linearity of an oxygen molecule. On my machine, these codes will give:\n```\n[-1.04036247e+21  4.26266450e+01  4.26266450e+01]\nREGULAR\n```\nApparently, the oxygen molecule is a linear molecule, but the `_get_rotor_type` function returns `REGULAR` not `LINEAR`. It is because the rotation constants can sometimes be a very negative number probably due to some numerical errors. The `_get_rotor_type` function assumes that all rotation constants are positive values (it is true as physically they should be positive). This bug will make the `harmonic_analysis` function in `pyscf.hessian.thermo` returns an empty frequency list. \n\nI suggest modifying the `_get_rotor_type` function from \n```python\ndef _get_rotor_type(rot_const):\n    if numpy.all(rot_const > 1e8):\n        rotor_type = 'ATOM'\n    elif rot_const[0] > 1e8 and (rot_const[1] - rot_const[2] < 1e-3):\n        rotor_type = 'LINEAR'\n    else:\n        rotor_type = 'REGULAR'\n    return rotor_type\n```\nto\n```python\ndef _get_rotor_type(rot_const):\n    if numpy.all(numpy.abs(rot_const) > 1e8):\n        rotor_type = 'ATOM'\n    elif numpy.abs(rot_const[0]) > 1e8 and (rot_const[1] - rot_const[2] < 1e-3):\n        rotor_type = 'LINEAR'\n    else:\n        rotor_type = 'REGULAR'\n    return rotor_type\n```\n\n**Version and hardware:**\n- PySCF version 2.4.0 installed via pip\n- numpy version 1.26.2\n- Operating system: Ubuntu\n\n", "hints_text": "Yes, this looks like a division by numerical zero issue. Probably better is that `rotational_const()` should return the absolute value of `e`. The principal moments of inertia should all be positive (or exactly zero). \nI agree. The three constants should be non-negative. \r\nThanks, Tim!\nI'll leave this open for a few days in case anyone else has other suggestions. After that, I can submit a bugfix PR.\nWhere are we on this issue? Is there a pull request open already?\nI recently converted a student lab to PySCF and ran across this. Here's how I monkey patched `pyscf.thermo.rotation_const` along with a basic test. In a nutshell, I just took the absolute value of the inertia tensor eigenvalues. Found this bug report afterwards. Seems like an easy fix.\n\n```python\nimport numpy\nfrom pyscf import gto\nfrom pyscf.data import nist\nfrom pyscf.hessian import thermo\n\n# Simple linear molecule.\nmol = gto.M(\n    atom=\"\"\"\n    H 0.00000000e+00, 0.00000000e+00, 0.00000000e+00\n    F 5.42619291e-15, 4.30752871e-14, 1.74376032e+00\n    \"\"\"\n)\n\n# Copied from thermo.harmonic_analysis to set up the direct function call to `thermo.rotation_const`.\nmass = mass = mol.atom_mass_list()\natom_coords = mol.atom_coords()\nmass_center = numpy.einsum(\"z,zx->x\", mass, atom_coords) / mass.sum()\natom_coords = atom_coords - mass_center\n\n# Call the problematic function directly.\nrot_const_wrong = thermo.rotation_const(mass, atom_coords)\nrotor_type_wrong = thermo._get_rotor_type(rot_const_wrong)\n\n# Print the wrong results.\nprint(f\"Rotation constants before patch: {rot_const_wrong}\")\nprint(f\"Rotor type before patch: {rotor_type_wrong}\")\n\n\n# Patched upstream function.\ndef rotation_const_patch(mass, atom_coords, unit=\"GHz\"):\n    \"\"\"Rotational constants to characterize rotational spectra\n\n    Kwargs:\n        unit (string) : One of GHz, wavenumber\n    \"\"\"\n    mass_center = numpy.einsum(\"z,zr->r\", mass, atom_coords) / mass.sum()\n    r = atom_coords - mass_center\n    im = numpy.einsum(\"z,zr,zs->rs\", mass, r, r)\n    im = numpy.eye(3) * im.trace() - im\n    # Patched the next line to take the absolute value.\n    e = numpy.sort(numpy.abs(numpy.linalg.eigvalsh(im)))\n\n    unit_im = nist.ATOMIC_MASS * (nist.BOHR_SI) ** 2\n    unit_hz = nist.HBAR / (4 * numpy.pi * unit_im)\n    with numpy.errstate(divide=\"ignore\"):\n        if unit.lower() == \"ghz\":\n            e = unit_hz / e * 1e-9\n        elif unit.lower() == \"wavenumber\":\n            e = unit_hz / e / nist.LIGHT_SPEED_SI * 1e-2\n        else:\n            raise RuntimeError(\"Unsupported unit \" + unit)\n    return e\n\n\n# Monkey patch thermo.rotation_const.\nthermo.rotation_const = rotation_const_patch\n\n# Call the problematic function directly.\nrot_const_right = thermo.rotation_const(mass, atom_coords)\nrotor_type_right = thermo._get_rotor_type(rot_const_right)\n\n# Print the correct results.\nprint(f\"Rotation constants after patch: {rot_const_right}\")\nprint(f\"Rotor type after patch: {rotor_type_right}\")\n```\n\nOutput:\n```\nRotation constants before patch: [-1.80399194e+31  1.74952443e+02  1.74952443e+02]\nRotor type before patch: REGULAR\nRotation constants after patch: [1.80399194e+31 1.74952443e+02 1.74952443e+02]\nRotor type after patch: LINEAR\n```\n\nPS: This worked for my problems. On a second thought, it might be safer to clip the eigenvalues to some small value to avoid division by zero.\n\n```python\ne = numpy.sort(numpy.linalg.eigvalsh(im))\neps = 1.0e-12\ne = numpy.maximum(e, eps)\n```\n\nI think we can use something like `e[e < 1e-9] = 0.0 ` after \nhttps://github.com/pyscf/pyscf/blob/c8a4215308657274f221937e5a8b8908a039c3a9/pyscf/hessian/thermo.py#L121\n\nSo the final rot_const[0] will be inf, and it's > 1e8.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Yes, this looks like a division by numerical zero issue. Probably better is that `rotational_const()` should return the absolute value of `e`. The principal moments of inertia should all be positive (or exactly zero). \nI agree. The three constants should be non-negative. \r\nThanks, Tim!\nI'll leave this open for a few days in case anyone else has other suggestions. After that, I can submit a bugfix PR.\nWhere are we on this issue? Is there a pull request open already?\nI recently converted a student lab to PySCF and ran across this. Here's how I monkey patched `pyscf.thermo.rotation_const` along with a basic test. In a nutshell, I just took the absolute value of the inertia tensor eigenvalues. Found this bug report afterwards. Seems like an easy fix.\n\n```python\nimport numpy\nfrom pyscf import gto\nfrom pyscf.data import nist\nfrom pyscf.hessian import thermo\n\n# Simple linear molecule.\nmol = gto.M(\n    atom=\"\"\"\n    H 0.00000000e+00, 0.00000000e+00, 0.00000000e+00\n    F 5.42619291e-15, 4.30752871e-14, 1.74376032e+00\n    \"\"\"\n)\n\n# Copied from thermo.harmonic_analysis to set up the direct function call to `thermo.rotation_const`.\nmass = mass = mol.atom_mass_list()\natom_coords = mol.atom_coords()\nmass_center = numpy.einsum(\"z,zx->x\", mass, atom_coords) / mass.sum()\natom_coords = atom_coords - mass_center\n\n# Call the problematic function directly.\nrot_const_wrong = thermo.rotation_const(mass, atom_coords)\nrotor_type_wrong = thermo._get_rotor_type(rot_const_wrong)\n\n# Print the wrong results.\nprint(f\"Rotation constants before patch: {rot_const_wrong}\")\nprint(f\"Rotor type before patch: {rotor_type_wrong}\")\n\n\n# Patched upstream function.\ndef rotation_const_patch(mass, atom_coords, unit=\"GHz\"):\n    \"\"\"Rotational constants to characterize rotational spectra\n\n    Kwargs:\n        unit (string) : One of GHz, wavenumber\n    \"\"\"\n    mass_center = numpy.einsum(\"z,zr->r\", mass, atom_coords) / mass.sum()\n    r = atom_coords - mass_center\n    im = numpy.einsum(\"z,zr,zs->rs\", mass, r, r)\n    im = numpy.eye(3) * im.trace() - im\n    # Patched the next line to take the absolute value.\n    e = numpy.sort(numpy.abs(numpy.linalg.eigvalsh(im)))\n\n    unit_im = nist.ATOMIC_MASS * (nist.BOHR_SI) ** 2\n    unit_hz = nist.HBAR / (4 * numpy.pi * unit_im)\n    with numpy.errstate(divide=\"ignore\"):\n        if unit.lower() == \"ghz\":\n            e = unit_hz / e * 1e-9\n        elif unit.lower() == \"wavenumber\":\n            e = unit_hz / e / nist.LIGHT_SPEED_SI * 1e-2\n        else:\n            raise RuntimeError(\"Unsupported unit \" + unit)\n    return e\n\n\n# Monkey patch thermo.rotation_const.\nthermo.rotation_const = rotation_const_patch\n\n# Call the problematic function directly.\nrot_const_right = thermo.rotation_const(mass, atom_coords)\nrotor_type_right = thermo._get_rotor_type(rot_const_right)\n\n# Print the correct results.\nprint(f\"Rotation constants after patch: {rot_const_right}\")\nprint(f\"Rotor type after patch: {rotor_type_right}\")\n```\n\nOutput:\n```\nRotation constants before patch: [-1.80399194e+31  1.74952443e+02  1.74952443e+02]\nRotor type before patch: REGULAR\nRotation constants after patch: [1.80399194e+31 1.74952443e+02 1.74952443e+02]\nRotor type after patch: LINEAR\n```\n\nPS: This worked for my problems. On a second thought, it might be safer to clip the eigenvalues to some small value to avoid division by zero.\n\n```python\ne = numpy.sort(numpy.linalg.eigvalsh(im))\neps = 1.0e-12\ne = numpy.maximum(e, eps)\n```\n\nI think we can use something like `e[e < 1e-9] = 0.0 ` after \nhttps://github.com/pyscf/pyscf/blob/c8a4215308657274f221937e5a8b8908a039c3a9/pyscf/hessian/thermo.py#L121\n\nSo the final rot_const[0] will be inf, and it's > 1e8.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/pyscf/pyscf/commit/482848d0683b1c78aa7e16ce198461df947ea5a9", "https://github.com/pyscf/pyscf/commit/1775df6ee1c94fa4d448d6979b48d1189421ee08"], "created_at": "2026-04-25T09:32:05Z"}
